    "updated_at": "2022-03-28T11:52:37Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Maybe some context helps at least where my confusion came from: when I was initially confused about why remappings was not picking the overrides, I was in a version of forge where config subcommand didn't exist. Today when I see both commands there (config and remappings), and read the docs, I can infer that since \"config\" considers the overrides (that is, the \"effective\" values used), I would guess guess that remappings doesn't. My suggestion would be the following:\r\nEither:\r\n1- remove remappings subcommand altogether - user can see them anyways with output of config command;\r\n2- do something along the lines of what @onbjerg suggested about with optional flags;\r\n2- clarify exactly what remappings is useful for or how it interacts with the \"local repository\"  - what affects its output?\r\n3- Leave both commands but update documentation with something along the lines of:\r\nremappings - prints the effective remappings\r\nconfig - Print all effective configuration values.\r\nRelatedly, I didn't find in the forge docs a documentation similar to what we have in dapp-tools on the order of precedence related to config variables, environment vars, etc. I just tried changing the value of remappings in the foundry.toml config file, yet I didn't see the change reflected in `forge remappings` - maybe I'm missing something here, but clarifying the whole topic in general in the docs would be beneficial imo. ",
